[{"id":"VR865041","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following statements correctly describes <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <msub> <mi>a</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </math></span></span>, and provides a correct justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR865041_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A can of beans of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>m</mi></math></span></span> is attached to the end of a vertical spring of spring constant <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"k\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"k\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>k</mi></math></span></span> that is secured to the ceiling. At time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 0\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"t equals 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>, the can is released from a position at which the spring is neither stretched or compressed and allowed to fall. At time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t sub 1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"t sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <msub> <mi>t</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </math></span></span>, the can has moved a downward distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d equals the fraction m g over k\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"d equals the fraction m g over k\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><mi>k</mi></mfrac></mstyle></math></span></span> from its initial position, and the acceleration of the can is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a can of mass m suspended from the end of a vertical spring of spring constant k that is attached to a ceiling.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR865041.g01.svg\" /></div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1 equals 0\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1 equals 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the can is at the equilibrium position of the can-spring-Earth system.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1 equals 0\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1 equals 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the velocity of the can is downwards and the force of the spring on the can is upwards.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1 equals maximum\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1 equals maximum\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mtext>maximum</mtext></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the speed of the can is at its maximum.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"a sub 1 equals maximum\"><math alttext=\"a sub 1 equals maximum\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mi>a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mtext>maximum</mtext></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the displacement of the can and the force of gravity on the can are in the same direction.</p>"],"answer":0}]